<sect> Usage <p>

In this section, we will explain you the basis to actually be able to play Boson.
The first thing to know is that, because of the lack of any IA player (artificial intelligence),
you won't be able to play alone. You need to have at least another player to play against.

<sect1> Launching the server <p>

The <tt/server/ is the central piece of the game, the place where everything is coordinated, and the
link between the different players. It must be launched on one and only one computer. Let's say for
the example that this computer is called 'eagle'

If you have successfully installed boson, you should have a program called <tt/boserver/. 
This is the first program to launch so that every single player may connect to it.

You should run it in <tt/background/, typing
<tscreen><verb>
[eagle]% boserver&
</verb></tscreen>

You can also click on <tt/boserver/, in the <tt/K-Menu/, under the group <tt/Games/.

Don't worry about the still naked interface of it, just hide it if you don't like it, there's nothing
in the window, but it _does_ do a lot of things behing.

<sect1> Launching Boson<p>

	Every single player should perform this step on his computer. There is no problem if
one of them is on the same computer as the server.

<tscreen><verb>
[gauss]% boson eagle&
</verb></tscreen>

By giving the <tt/eagle/ argument to boson, you tell him on which computer he can find the server
in order to connect to it.

You can also click on <tt/boson/, in the <tt/K-Menu/, under the group <tt/Games/, but doing this way
you won't be able to give any argument, so that boson will try to connect to the same computer. You can do this
only if the boserver has been launched on _your_ computer.

There will soon be <tt/icons/-to-click-on-to-get-things-simplier, but until then, you need
to performs all of those steps.


